// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  THE PEOPLING OF AMERICA, 1600–2020  ·  v2, county-anchored
//
//  WHAT CHANGED: dots are no longer hand-placed blobs. Every dot is anchored
//  to a REAL county, sampled in proportion to that county's actual population
//  by race/ethnicity (2020-era Census estimates, 3,100 continental counties).
//  So Memphis reads majority-Black, East Tennessee reads white-British, the
//  Mississippi Delta and the Black Belt light up, the cities cluster by their
//  true density, and the Southwest carries its Hispanic weight.
//
//  HONEST SOURCING:
//   • Black, Hispanic, Asian, and Native placements = real county data.
//   • The split of the WHITE population into European ancestries (English,
//     Scots-Irish, German, Irish, Italian, Scandinavian, Jewish, French) is
//     a MODELED regional estimate (no keyless county ancestry source), but it
//     is anchored to the real white-population totals of each county.
//   • Native presence before ~1900 is a modeled historical layer (continent-
//     wide, then fading with dispossession); modern Native dots sit on real
//     reservation/urban counties.
//   • Each dot ≈ a representative slice of people (~100k), not an individual.
//   • Borders are modern-state approximations of historical claims.
//
//  Dots ARRIVE (fade in at a port/frontier) and MOVE to their real county
//  home as the slider advances — so you see the Great Migration north, the
//  westward settlement frontier, the post-1965 Hispanic & Asian diffusion,
//  and the contraction of Native nations.
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

